1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,619
Charbel Samuel Aoun is a working artist in the Middle Eastern nation of Lebanon.

2
00:00:07,619 --> 00:00:24,615
As the Israeli military launches a deadly attack against the militant group Hezbollah in his home country, Aoun asks, "Does art still have a place in such a crisis?"

3
00:00:24,615 --> 00:00:33,235
Lebanon has long played an important part in the Arab world's artistic community.

4
00:00:33,235 --> 00:00:43,306
It has been a center for arts, music and theater, combining traditional and modern influences.

5
00:00:43,306 --> 00:01:04,055
Now, Lebanese artists are using their work as a way to express the anger and loss they feel after a year-long Israeli offensive that has killed more than 3,200 people, most of them since September.

6
00:01:04,055 --> 00:01:11,707
Aoun's works of art are directly connected to the conflicts Lebanon has seen.

7
00:01:11,707 --> 00:01:27,565
In 2013, he began gathering dust from Syrian refugee camps in Lebanon to create a series of paintings before moving on to explore other materials.

8
00:01:27,565 --> 00:01:44,912
Now, he says the darkness and hopelessness of the war and the waste left behind by Israel's intense bombing campaign have renewed his desire to create art from dust.

9
00:01:44,912 --> 00:01:54,120
"You either stop everything or keep going with the little that still has meaning," he said.

10
00:01:54,120 --> 00:02:00,088
Two of his exhibitions have been canceled due to the war.

11
00:02:00,088 --> 00:02:16,786
While he once made money from selling art, he now also relies on selling honey from his beehives, which he first set up as a project to create art from beeswax.

12
00:02:16,786 --> 00:02:22,184
"I can no longer rely on the art market," he said.

13
00:02:22,184 --> 00:02:29,198
Exhibition spaces across Beirut have closed in recent months.

14
00:02:29,198 --> 00:02:36,921
Their owners told Reuters there is no demand to buy art at this time.

15
00:02:36,921 --> 00:02:46,017
Even Lebanon's famous Sursock Museum has stored its collections underground.

16
00:02:46,017 --> 00:02:56,714
Lebanese singer and musician Joy Fayad has also struggled with the emotional cost of the conflict.

17
00:02:56,714 --> 00:03:02,077
It has made it difficult for her to perform for months.

18
00:03:02,077 --> 00:03:14,900
"It limited my creativity; it was like I shut down. I couldn't give to others, nor to myself," Fayad, 36, said.

19
00:03:14,900 --> 00:03:20,436
Instead, she threw her energy into songwriting.

20
00:03:20,436 --> 00:03:36,259
One line in a new song reads: "You are from the downtrodden people, whose word has been silenced, and by their weapons, you are paying the price with your blood."

21
00:03:36,259 --> 00:03:49,656
She recently began performing again, singing for displaced and refugee children in Lebanon at an event north of Beirut.

22
00:03:49,656 --> 00:04:05,326
"They're changing the atmosphere, having fun after such a difficult period," she said, especially for those who became used to the sound of bombs instead of music.

23
00:04:05,326 --> 00:04:09,522
I’m Andrew Smith.